<p><b>Paul Ralph Ehrlich</b> (born 29 May 1932 ) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Entomologist" title="Entomologist" class="mw-redirect">entomologist</a> specializing in <a href="/wiki/Lepidoptera" title="Lepidoptera">Lepidoptera</a> (butterflies). He became a <a href="/wiki/Household_name" title="Household name" class="mw-redirect">household name</a><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> after publication of his 1968 book <i><a href="/wiki/The_Population_Bomb" title="The Population Bomb">The Population Bomb</a></i>, in which he predicted that "In the 1970s and 1980s . . . hundreds of millions of people are going to starve to death in spite of any crash programs embarked upon now." <sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Ehrlich is Bing Professor of Population Studies in the department of Biological Sciences at <a href="/wiki/Stanford_University" title="Stanford University">Stanford University</a><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup>.</p>
